{"id":14881605,"mediaExerciseId":"918c0786-0f15-461a-8ea9-3543b4e9c4c7","exerciseName":"7","chapterName":"17","chapterTitle":"Dividends and Payout Policy","groupId":612429,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":603,"solutions":[{"id":5994977,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to determine the ex-dividend price of the company.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/418392527f0028070761cef507d09f36/41e3aebeaf01d4d685e09a978ea511c5/lateximg_large.png","width":993},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/418392527f0028070761cef507d09f36/41e3aebeaf01d4d685e09a978ea511c5/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**Ex-dividend** is a stock state in which the shareholders are not entitled to receive any dividends, and stock prices no longer include the dividends. The ex-dividend price measures the stock price decrease as the stock goes ex-dividend.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":138,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/418392527f0028070761cef507d09f36/a9c2163a49422ef114792f3599e3d38e/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/418392527f0028070761cef507d09f36/a9c2163a49422ef114792f3599e3d38e/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's identify the given amounts needed tp solve the problem:\n\n| |Amounts | \n|--|--:| \n| Equity | $ 508,000| \n| Share Outstanding|12,000 sh | \n| Stock Dividend Percentage |25% | ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Since the company has declared a 25 percent stock dividend, we will compute the new share outstanding by multiplying the share outstanding by the stock dividend percentage. \n\n$$\\begin{aligned} \n\\text{New Shares Outstanding} &= \\text{Share Outstanding}\\times{\\text{(1+r})}\\\\[5pt] \n&= \\text{12,000}\\times{\\text{(1+ 0.25})}\\\\[5pt] \n&= \\text{12,000}\\times{\\text{1.25}}\\\\[5pt] \n&=\\boxed{\\textbf{15,000 shares}}\\\\ \n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nTherefore, the new shares outstanding after the stock dividend are 15,000 shares.\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":446,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/418392527f0028070761cef507d09f36/ebfaf1fdd66c82e54036bc5684a249bb/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":225,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/08/418392527f0028070761cef507d09f36/ebfaf1fdd66c82e54036bc5684a249bb/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, to get the ex-dividend price, we will divide the equity value by the new shares outstanding. \n\n$$ \\begin{aligned}\n\\text{Ex-dividend Price} &= \\dfrac{\\text{Equity}}{\\text{New Shares Outstanding}}\\\\[10pt]\n&= \\dfrac{\\text{\\$\\hspace{5pt}508,000}}{\\text{15,000}}\\\\[10pt]\n&=\\boxed{\\textbf{\\$ 33.87}}\\\\ \n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nTherefore, the ex-dividend price of the company is **$33.87**.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"969fe184-0bc4-4a45-b54c-353b0068ee6b","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg",